ce:section.ce:para:
In this study, alendronate was selected as the carbon precursor for the preparation of highly efficient Alen-CDs with prominent anti-osteoporosis property. As a well-established drug for treating bone- and calcium metabolism-related diseases, alendronate has been widely used clinically. However, alendronate is frequently impeded from low water solubility and bioavailability. Furthermore, as a nonfluorescent drug, it's impossible to track its distributions in vivo. Thus, this study was aimed to conquer these challenges via the simple carbonization of alendronate to form Alen-CDs, which could inherit the intrinsic anti-osteoporosis property of alendronate while achieve much enhanced water solubility and bioavailability as well as the bonus of PL (Fig. 1
                        a
                        ). In addition, the biocompatibility of Alen-CDs was also expected to be improved as the carbonization could generally reduce the cytotoxicity of raw materials. To our delight, fluorescent Alen-CDs were indeed successfully synthesized by hydrothermal treatment (entries 1–2, Table S1) or microwave irradiation by a domestic microwave oven (entry 3, Table S1); while microwave irradiation by a microwave synthesizer did not result anything fluorescent (entries 6–12, Table S1). The brownish gelatin sample with preferred hydrophilicity from hydrothermal treatment of alendronate at 200 °C for 24 h (entry 2, Table S1) was selected for further analysis considering their relatively better PL performance (Fig. S1).

Next, the chemical composition and surface functionalities of Alen-CDs were carefully evaluated by FTIR and XPS. As shown in the FTIR spectrum (Fig. 2
                        a
                        ), the absorption band at 3430 cm−1 was attributed to the NH stretching [36], which might be inherited from the carbon precursor alendronate. The peaks at 2410, 1131 and 950 cm−1 were ascribed to the phosphorous stretching of PH, PO3 and P-O-H, respectively, which were also inherited from the carbon precursor. On the other hand, the peaks at 1630 and 1382 cm−1 were assigned to the stretching vibrations of CC and CN, respectively, which might be originated due to the formation of Alen-CDs. The FTIR absorption bands indicated the rich presence of amine, hydroxyl group and phosphorous on the surface of Alen-CDs.
